1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,000
Hey Oscar, big Will and Grace fan, huh?

2
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:11,000
No. Everybody assumes I am. I always give them as gifts.

3
00:00:11,000 --> 00:00:16,000
Oh. Dunder Mifflin is having our first ever garage sale.

4
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:20,000
Like many Americans, we realized we had a lot of things that we didn't really need.

5
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:25,000
And ten cents of every dollar is going into the party fund so we can throw parties for ourselves.

6
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:30,000
Finally got up. Cut that off the wall.

7
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:45,000
Looks like we're in the Spice District.

8
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:47,000
Yep.

9
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:50,000
Taking a ride on Spice Mountain.

10
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:53,000
People!

11
00:00:53,000 --> 00:00:57,000
People! Look alive! It's show time!

12
00:00:57,000 --> 00:01:03,000
Doors open in three, two, one!

13
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:10,000
Ooh, yikes.

14
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:13,000
It's cold, White. Just shut the door and let people come in the front.

15
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:16,000
It's good that it's cold. It will drive business inside.

16
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:18,000
The signs will drive business inside.

17
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:21,000
The warmth will lure people inside.

18
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:24,000
This is how business works. I'm not closing the door.

19
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:26,000
Close it.

20
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:40,000
Uh oh. Looks like someone's signs a little crooked.

21
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:43,000
Looks awful.

22
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:45,000
Need a thumbtack? Sure. Not so fast.

23
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:50,000
Shrewts are farmers by hobby and traders by trade.

24
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:56,000
Through the art of the swap, I will walk out of this garage sale with the finest item here.

25
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:59,000
I will trade you for the used candle.

26
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:00,000
Forget you.

27
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:05,000
Come on. It's trash. Like your sign unless you have this.

28
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:08,000
Fine. Just get it.

29
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:11,000
That's how it's done.

30
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:14,000
Whoa. I love her. How much for that?

31
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:19,000
I, uh, I actually don't know why I brought that because it's kind of priceless.

32
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:21,000
Ten dollars.

33
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:24,000
No, I paid five hundred dollars for that.

34
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:27,000
Two hundred. Five hundred. Twenty. Forty-five. Get lost.

35
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:28,000
Damn it.

36
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:30,000
And that is how you do it.

37
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:32,000
You know, we don't have to sell that if you don't want.

38
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:35,000
If it's a problem with the neon, I can have my neon guy take a look.

39
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:39,000
No, but you know what? It's really more for a bachelor pad. I just want to get a fair price.

40
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:42,000
Well, we could put it in storage in case.

41
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:44,000
In case? In case of what?

42
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:48,000
You know, in case maybe something changes.

43
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:51,000
I don't have it in case. Do you have it in case?

44
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:53,000
No.

45
00:02:55,000 --> 00:02:58,000
How much for the slip and slide?

46
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:00,000
Get lost.

47
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:04,000
Yes. Hello, Mr. Flax. This is Michael Scott, your daughter's boss.

48
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:09,000
I am calling because I am going to have to fire your daughter Holly

49
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:12,000
because she's such a terrible employee.

50
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:15,000
I'm just kidding. I'm kidding.

51
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:19,000
I'm actually calling because I'm in love with her.

52
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:22,000
I love your daughter and I have for some time.

53
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:29,000
And I would like to discuss my intentions with you, which are to ask her to marry me.

54
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:33,000
And I was just hoping that you would give me your approval.

55
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:36,000
And this isn't a joke. So call me back when you get this.

56
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:40,000
I'll take this and I look forward to speaking. Thank you.

57
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:47,000
Are you serious? A half-used candle?

58
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:50,000
Get out of here, Dwight. You're blocking my table with your giant body.

59
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:54,000
Oh, because there's a huge line of people who want your spinster tchotchkes.

60
00:03:54,000 --> 00:03:56,000
Screw you, man. People like my stuff.

61
00:03:56,000 --> 00:03:58,000
People like Ryan?

62
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Let me tell you about men like him.

63
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:03,000
He comes over and you're like, hey, baby, let me light a candle.

64
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:06,000
And you pull out this one, half-used.

65
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:11,000
He's like, who else is she seeing? I better lock her down fast.

66
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:15,000
You can take my Helen Fielding collection.

67
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:17,000
And the Jennifer Weiner collection.

68
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:21,000
Oh my gosh, you have the Dallas board game?

69
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:24,000
Yeah. When I was a kid, I was on Dallas.

70
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:25,000
Really?

71
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Yeah. We missed our connecting flight and we spent the entire day on Dallas.

72
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:33,000
Then we spent a week on Hawaii. I was on heaven.

73
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:36,000
We should play it.

74
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:38,000
Well, there's no instructions.

75
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:40,000
It's Dallas. The game. We can figure it out.

76
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:43,000
Yeah. I'm pretty good at board games.

77
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:46,000
Well, shall we make it a little interesting?

78
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:47,000
Sure.

79
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:55,000
What is this?

80
00:04:56,000 --> 00:04:58,000
How did those get out? I'm sorry.

81
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:03,000
Professor Copperfield's Miracle Lagoons?

82
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:06,000
I was in Jamaica and I got lost.

83
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:09,000
And it was getting dark this one night and then out of nowhere,

84
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:12,000
this guy comes with a cart and he's selling these.

85
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:15,000
Dwight, he told me things about myself that there's no way he could have known.

86
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:17,000
That's a common swindler's trick.

87
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:20,000
Probably. Probably.

88
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:23,000
So I buy some. I turn the corner. I feel like an idiot.

89
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:26,000
So I go back to get my money. He was gone.

90
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:31,000
So you want to sell me magic beans?

91
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:37,000
Correction, I do not want to sell you Professor Copperfield's Miracle Lagoons.

92
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:41,000
Nice try. No, correction. Terrible try.

93
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:48,000
Michael called Dad?

94
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:50,000
Your friend Michael, yes. What's going on?

95
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:55,000
I think I know, but I'll sound stupid if I'm wrong. Is Dad there?

96
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:57,000
Hollis? Hi, Dad.

97
00:05:57,000 --> 00:06:00,000
There was a program on TV about India.

98
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:03,000
Okay. Did you connect with Michael?

99
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:05,000
You want to watch it?

100
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:09,000
I'm not there, Dad. I'm in Pennsylvania.

101
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:11,000
What are you doing there?

102
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:15,000
I live here. Can I talk to you about Michael?

103
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:17,000
I'll put your mother on.

104
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:18,000
No, no, no, Dad.

105
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:19,000
Holli?

106
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:22,000
Mom, Dad can't seem to focus on a subject.

107
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:24,000
Don't you worry about him. He's got me.

108
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:26,000
Well, who do you have?

109
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:29,000
I have your father. He's right here. I'll put him on.

110
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:31,000
No, Mom.

111
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:36,000
Dunder Mifflin, this is Gabe. How may I direct your call?

112
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:40,000
I've been demoted.

113
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:43,000
No, I'm just holding down the fort.

114
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:46,000
Aaron's job is so easy.

115
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:51,000
Your mail. Sealed with a kiss. My own personal touch.

116
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:54,000
And I'm done with the mail.

117
00:06:56,000 --> 00:06:59,000
Oh, which one's decaf?

118
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:01,000
Michael?

119
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:17,000
Michael! Michael! Hey!

120
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:18,000
Hi!

121
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:20,000
I was just coming out to see what you were doing and maybe stop you.

122
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:23,000
Oh, you know what? Do you have a siphon? I think I'm going to run out of gas.

123
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:25,000
Why do you need more gas?

124
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:28,000
Well, I'm writing a message.

125
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:30,000
Is it a good message or a bad message?

126
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:33,000
I'm asking Holly a question in fire.

127
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:35,000
Are you proposing?

128
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:37,000
Maybe.

129
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:41,000
Oh, you know what? I've got gas on my hands and my shoes.

130
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:44,000
Would you light it? Do the honors, please.

131
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:46,000
Yeah, yeah, no problem.

132
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:50,000
Pam?

133
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:51,000
Yep?

134
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:52,000
Could you light this, please?

135
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:55,000
Michael, you've had two ideas today.

136
00:07:55,000 --> 00:07:59,000
And one of them was great. And the other one was terrible.

137
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:01,000
I am not in the mood for riddles, Pam.

138
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:03,000
This is terrible.

139
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:04,000
No, this is romantic.

140
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:07,000
You know what? I'm going to get a hose and then we'll talk about it.

141
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:11,000
Okay, we'll figure it out. I'll be right back. Just stay there.

142
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:15,000
I'm going to ask Holly to marry me today.

143
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:21,000
Free sample?

144
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:24,000
My mom makes the best pesto in the world.

145
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:27,000
And I always tell her, Mom, you should sell this. You'd make a fortune.

146
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:29,000
And she always says, no, it's just for family.

147
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:32,000
Well, finally, I was like, f*** it, I'll sell it.

148
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:37,000
So I'm like, Mom, I need you to make a ton of pesto for a pesto party for all my friends.

149
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:40,000
She's like, oh, okay. Pesto party? Really?

150
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:44,000
Anyway, she makes like a hundred bottles worth. It's so good.

151
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:49,000
And Phyllis just had that mom look I wanted.
